<figureCitation id="15872A2EFFFCFF8AA8887221FD48FC8D" box="[675,691,799,825]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="6.[170,203,994,1016]" captionTargetBox="[174,1200,175,940]" captionTargetId="figure-280@6.[170,1217,170,968]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Fig. 3. Popovineura nacta, male, holotype (SIZK, N K–666): 1 — general appearance; 2 — scape, pedicel, flagellomeres 1–2; 3 — flagellomeres 5–6; 4 — flagellomeres 8–11; 5 — palpus; 6 — fore tarsus; 7 — fore tarsomere 5; 8 — genitalia. Scale bars 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6452797" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6452797/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="48">3</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="15872A2EFFFCFF8AA8947221FD36FC8D" box="[703,717,799,825]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="7.[175,208,1630,1652]" captionTargetBox="[174,758,913,1615]" captionTargetId="figure-501@7.[174,758,913,1616]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Fig. 4. Nascensluna mellea, female, holotype (SIZK, N K–1601): 1 — general appearance; 2 — flagellomeres 8–10; 3 — flagellomere 5; 4 — ovipositor. Scale bars 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6452799" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6452799/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="48">4</figureCitation>
</emphasis>
). Body (without genitalia) is 1.3 times longer than antennae. Wings are 1.3 times as long as antennae. Antennae are 2+12-segmented. Head with large eyes that laterally cover only dorsal part of head. Scape is enlarged distally, almost as long as wide round pedicel. First flagellomere slightly longer than 2nd, its neck is shorter than the neck of the 2nd one; 5th flagellomere is 1.9 times as long as wide, its neck is 3.0 times shorter than basal enlargement. Tenth and 11th flagellomeres have very short neck; 10th flagellomere is 1.5 times as long as wide; 11th flagellomere is slightly narrowed distally and shorter than 10th. 12th flagellomere is oviform. Palpi are very narrow, 2–3-segmented, slightly swollen laterally. Fore tarsus with 2nd tarsomere 5 times as long as 1st. Wing is 2.2 times as long as wide. Vein R 
<subScript id="113834EEFFFCFF8AA89C756CFD2AFBD4" attach="left" box="[695,721,1106,1120]" fontSize="6" pageId="13" pageNumber="48">1+2</subScript>
joins C before its midlength; R 
<subScript id="113834EEFFFCFF8AAE11756CFBAFFBD4" attach="none" box="[1082,1108,1106,1120]" fontSize="6" pageId="13" pageNumber="48">4+5</subScript>
is strongly curved near apex, joins the wing margin closer to the apex than Cu 
<subScript id="113834EEFFFCFF8AA9EA754CFC32FB34" attach="left" box="[961,969,1138,1152]" fontSize="6" pageId="13" pageNumber="48">2</subScript>
. All tibiae subequal to or longer than respective femora. Fore tibia 1.2 times as long as femur. Hind leg is longer than fore and middle ones. Gonocoxites are slightly rounded laterally, 2.6 times as long as wide. Gonostylus is slightly curved, almost parallelsided, with wide apical claw, 1.7 times shorter than gonocoxites. Cerci are wider than gonocoxites. Aedeagus almost triangular.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8D0336ABFFFCFF8AAAC8743EFB32FA4D" blockId="13.[174,1233,799,1850]" pageId="13" pageNumber="48">M e a s u r e m e n t s, mm: body length, 0.76 (without genitalia); 0.83 (with genitalia); wing length, 0.77; wing width, 0.35; antennal length, 0.59; head length, 0.20 (without mouth parts); 0.25 (with mouth parts); width of lateral side of head, 0.11; palpi length, 0.12; thorax length, 0.28; abdomen length, 0.41; length of fore leg, 1.38; coxa and trochanter, 0.09; tarsus, 0.61; femur 0.32; tibia 0.36; 1st segment, 0.06, 2nd, 0.30; 3rd, 0.06; 4th, 0.09; 5th, 0.07; length of middle: leg, 1.31; femur 0.33; tibia 0.37; tarsus, 0.61; coxa and trochanter, 0.09; 1st segment, 0.06, 2nd, 0.28; 3rd, 0.12; 4th, 0.09; 5th, 0.06; length of hind: leg, 1.46; coxa and trochanter, 0.09; tarsus, 0.66; femur, 0.34; tibia, 0.37; 1st segment, 0.06, 2nd, 0.32; 3rd, 0.11; 4th, 0.10; 5th, 0.07.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8D0336ABFFFCFF8AAAC874C1FBC6F90D" blockId="13.[174,1233,799,1850]" pageId="13" pageNumber="48">
C o m p a r i s o n. By the shape of the body, wing venation, long legs and form of flagellomeres the new species is closely related to 
<taxonomicName id="4ABC4D28FFFCFF8AA8E47721FB2AF98D" authority="Fedotova et Perkovsky, 2008" authorityName="Fedotova et Perkovsky" authorityYear="2008" box="[719,1233,1567,1594]" class="Insecta" family="Cecidomyiidae" genus="Ledomyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="48" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dextra">
<emphasis id="BFC8EAB9FFFCFF8AA8E47721FC77F98D" box="[719,908,1567,1593]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="48">Ledomyia dextra</emphasis>
Fedotova et Perkovsky, 2008
</taxonomicName>
from Dubrovitsa, differing from it by the 2+12-segmented antennae (vs. 2+11 of 
<taxonomicName id="4ABC4D28FFFCFF8AAE72777EFB3BF9ED" authorityName="Fedotova et Perkovsky" authorityYear="2008" box="[1113,1216,1599,1625]" class="Insecta" family="Cecidomyiidae" genus="Ledomyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="48" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dextra">
<emphasis id="BFC8EAB9FFFCFF8AAE72777EFB3BF9ED" box="[1113,1216,1599,1625]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="48">L. dextra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); wing ratio (2.2 vs. 2.6); very long 2nd tarsomere; wider and shorter middle flagellomeres with wide and short necks; all tibiae longer than respective femora (hind tibia of 
<taxonomicName id="4ABC4D28FFFCFF8AAE3A77BEFB8CF92D" authorityName="Fedotova et Perkovsky" authorityYear="2008" box="[1041,1143,1663,1689]" class="Insecta" family="Cecidomyiidae" genus="Ledomyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="48" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dextra">
<emphasis id="BFC8EAB9FFFCFF8AAE3A77BEFB8CF92D" box="[1041,1143,1663,1689]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="48">L. dextra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
shorter than femur); oviform apical flagellomere (vs. oval of 
<taxonomicName id="4ABC4D28FFFCFF8AA92C779EFC96F90D" authorityName="Fedotova et Perkovsky" authorityYear="2008" box="[775,877,1695,1721]" class="Insecta" family="Cecidomyiidae" genus="Ledomyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="48" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dextra">
<emphasis id="BFC8EAB9FFFCFF8AA92C779EFC96F90D" box="[775,877,1695,1721]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="48">L. dextra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); larger body size.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8D0336ABFFFCFF8AAAC877FEFB86F96D" blockId="13.[174,1233,799,1850]" box="[227,1149,1727,1754]" pageId="13" pageNumber="48">E t y m o l o g y. The species is named after Olga — daughter of E. E. Perkovsky.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8D0336ABFFFCFF8AAAC877E1FDCBF88E" blockId="13.[174,1233,799,1850]" pageId="13" pageNumber="48">
All in all, in 
<collectingRegion id="4F78F849FFFCFF8AABAB77DEFE35F94E" box="[384,462,1760,1786]" country="Ukraine" name="Rivne" pageId="13" pageNumber="48">Rovno</collectingRegion>
amber 
<taxonomicName id="4ABC4D28FFFCFF8AA80677E1FD2AF94D" authorityName="Kieffer" authorityYear="1913" box="[557,721,1759,1785]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Brachineurini" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="35" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" sensu="lato">Brachineurini</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4ABC4D28FFFCFF8AA93977E1FC61F94D" authorityName="Enderlein" authorityYear="1936" box="[786,922,1759,1785]" class="Insecta" family="Cecidomyiidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="48" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Ledomyiini">Ledomyiini</taxonomicName>
account for 11.9 % of all species of the superfamily 
<taxonomicName id="4ABC4D28FFFCFF8AABCE77C1FD5EF8AD" box="[485,677,1791,1817]" class="Insecta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="48" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="superFamily" superFamily="Cecidomyioidea">Cecidomyioidea</taxonomicName>
(27 vs. 227), in Baltic amber — for 9.0 % (6 vs. 67) (
<bibRefCitation id="E92D4B5AFFFCFF8AAAC87621FDD8F88E" author="Fedotova, Z. A. &amp; Perkovsky, E. E." box="[227,547,1823,1850]" pageId="13" pageNumber="48" pagination="1101 - 1179" refId="ref9604" refString="Fedotova, Z. A., Perkovsky, E. E. New gall midges of the tribe Leptosynini (Diptera, Cecidomyiidae) from the Late Eocene Ambers and the classification of the supertribe Heteropezidi // Paleontol. J. - 2009. - 43, N 9. - P. 1101 - 1179." type="journal article" year="2009">Fedotova, Perkovsky, 2009</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
